description:
MVVM, bare knuckle style!
      Blue.MVVM is, and will remain, an ultra lightweight suite supporting your Model-View-ViewModel (MVVM) based applications.


      _about this package_

      This package includes binaries only. You should use this package for test projects or assemblies that need to interact with types in Blue.MVVM.
      For a head start, use Blue.MVVM (http://www.nuget.org/packages/Blue.MVVM/) instead.


      _what to expect in future releases?_

      There are many ideas around regarding upcoming releases of the Blue.MVVM suite.
      However, those updates will be shipped in form of additional packages. This way, you can add just those packages that best fits your application and needs.

      Upcoming releases may include, but are not limited to:
      + XML-comments
      - packages with samples
      - (fluid)validation
      - message broker
      - IoC-Container integration
      - public git-repo
      - many more...

      So stay tuned for updates!


      Send feedback, feature-request, unexpected breaking changes, etc. via the projects nuget-page, http://www.nuget.org/packages/Blue.MVVM.Lib/ContactOwners, until there is a projet homepage...
summary: MVVM, bare knuckle style! Ultra lightweight component suite for Model-View-ViewModel based applications. Binaries only.

description: Common classes for the Crocodev's projects

ChemBytes Draw is a compact .NET component allowing developers to integrate advanced chemical drawing and chemical information processing into any  .NET project (WPF or Windows Forms).

This is a 30 day evaluation version, which later can be unlocked. No registration required.

As part of a .NET application, ChemBytes Draw on demand displays a fully featured chemical drawing editor, which also supports organometallic, polymer and peptide drawing. Content can be imported from other third party chemical drawing tools, e.g. ISIS/Symyx/Accelrys Draw, ChemDraw, Marvin, etc., via MDL clipboard content or via MDL format export files, including V3000 format. When the user closes the editor, the API takes over and exposes the chemical information for use by your own application. Thus, the molecular weights and elemental formulas of all entered reactants and products, their InChIKeys, bitmap and vector images, bounding boxes, the MDL reaction and molfiles, and the internal file format for database storage, etc. are available for further processing. ChemBytes Draw is written in 100% managed code, i.e. it is no wrapper around an existing Java or C++ functionality.

A sample Visual Studio project and sample files are available from the project site.

Radial is a lightweight c# framework licensed under LGPL. It is designed to improve developers working efficiency, more convenient and efficient to build applications.It integrated with many components: 

• Dependency Injection (based on Unity) 
• Json (install Newtonsoft.Json first) 
• Serialization (Json, Xml, Binary) 
• Logging (based on log4net) 
• Caching (in-memory, or install EnyimMemcached first) 
• Persistence (install NHibernate first) 
• Web & Network (include MVC extensions, install Microsoft.AspNet.Mvc and Microsoft.AspNet.WebApi first) 
• Parameter (an easy way to store settings in xml or database) 
• ExcelTools (install EPPlus first) 
• Drawing (Captcha, ImageKits) 
• And Others...

You can add comments and specify keys and values without quotes.

Configuration files are edited by end-users, not developers. Users should not have to worry about putting commas in the correct place. Software should empower the user not hinder him.

For details click on the "Project Site" link or go to http://hjson.org.

Tested on .net & Mono.
summary: JSON for Humans, allows comments and is less error prone.

ChemBytes Draw is a compact .NET component allowing developers to integrate advanced chemical drawing and chemical information processing into any  .NET project (WPF or Windows Forms).

This is a 30 day evaluation version, which later can be unlocked. No registration required.

As part of a .NET application, ChemBytes Draw on demand displays a fully featured chemical drawing editor, which also supports organometallic, polymer and peptide drawing. Content can be imported from other third party chemical drawing tools, e.g. ISIS/Symyx/Accelrys Draw, ChemDraw, Marvin, etc., via MDL clipboard content or via MDL format export files, including V3000 format. When the user closes the editor, the API takes over and exposes the chemical information for use by your own application. Thus, the molecular weights and elemental formulas of all entered reactants and products, their InChIKeys, bitmap and vector images, bounding boxes, the MDL reaction and molfiles, and the internal file format for database storage, etc. are available for further processing. ChemBytes Draw is written in 100% managed code, i.e. it is no wrapper around an existing Java or C++ functionality.

A sample Visual Studio project and sample files are available from the project site.
